# INTRODUCTION

The stability and efficiency of modern power grids are linked to the ability to accurately forecast electricity demand. Time series forecasting plays a critical role in strategic planning across industries. Like weather forecasting, supply and demand forecasting in many industries, or health sickness treatment. In the energy sector it is critical to ensure reliability, efficiency, and sustainability of electric supply by forecasting future demand _(Singh et. al., 2013)_.

The importance of using regression techniques in this field is vital because electricity must be consumed at the same as it is generated. Accurate forecasting helps operators to match supply and demand in real-time; it also prevents blackouts or overloading on systems. Other advantages of forecasting are economic efficiency and dynamic pricing. Energy providers can reduce operating costs by optimizing electricity generation and purchases. Predicting the peak of the demand allows operators to better plan for the use of calculations to minimize cost inefficiency at power plants.

Additionally, time series forecasting provides information to utility companies to implement demand-based pricing. It also helps utility companies with long-term investment decisions. They can plan upgrades, maintenance, and expansions based on forecasts including the integration of renewable energy. It plays a crucial role in energy sources. Accurate demand predictions give more options in optimizing sources into the grid with stability.

This assignment contains relevant information on the topic of supply and demand forecasting. It applies time series regression techniques like linear regression and random forest regression to forecast electricity demand.

# Task 3: Regression Model Development and Evaluation

**3.1. Data Splitting and Scaling**

We need to check how well the models can perform on new data and a real-world forecasting scenario. To do that, we need to split the dataset chronologically and create validation and test for understanding the performance of algorithms. Iâ€™ve split the dataset using functions which are shown in Figure 13 below.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 13

%70 of the datasets were used for the training, the next 15 of the datasets were used for a model performance check and the final %15 of the datasets were used for testing and understanding how the model will perform on new data.

When working with time series datasets, it's critical to split them into chronological order _(James, D.A. and Pregibon, D., 1992)_. Unlike other data, we shouldnâ€™t mix time series data before splitting it into train, test, and validation parts. If we do that prediction models might learn future information and going, try predicting the past which makes the project unrealistic. To make this work I've used features to calculate index numbers where training and validation splits need to start and end. After that, I created train, test, and validation splits according to these indexes.

We need one more step before training regression models. For correct model performance training, test and validation splits need to be standardized using the StandartScaler function which can be seen in Figure 14 below.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Figure 14

Standardizing the data helps because it makes all the features have a similar scale a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one which can be sensitive to different feature scales. It also helps the model learn faster and more effectively.

# Task 4: Conclusions and Business Recommendations

This study demonstrated a methodological approach to forecasting short-term electricity demand in NSW using time series regression techniques. By systematically preprocessing the 6th month of the 2018 electricity demand dataset, engineering relevant temporal and lagged features, and applying Linear Regression and Random Forest Regression models.

The results from the test set show that the Linear Regression model provided slightly better results achieving an RÂ² score of 0.99. Also, feature importance analysis from the Linear Regression model highlighted the influence of recent past demands such as totaldemand\_lag\_1.

There are a few limitations in this study like using only one month of data limits the modelsâ€™ ability to train across different seasons and long-term trends. Also, there are some missing exogenous predictors such as detailed weather forecasts or specific economic indicators. Furthermore, while standard regression models were used, more advanced models or deep learning models were not in discussion for this study. According to these limitations, the findings from this study lead to the following strategic recommendations for energy efficiency, stakeholders, grid operators, and generation companies to improve their business:

1.  **Use Weather Data to Improve Forecasting:** Predictable daily patterns can easily be confirmed by the model, but the next crucial step could be implementing real-time weather forecast data into machine learning models. This system could allow more precise short-term demand predictions and give grid operators the chance to optimize load capacity _(Taylor, J.W. and Buizza, R., 2003)._
2.  **Optime Trading with High Frequency Demand:** Both models heavily rely on totaldemand\_lag\_1 which is demand from 30 minutes prior, market conditions change rapidly. Generation companies can build an automated system to implement algorithmic trading strategies for markets. Therefore, this system can provide them with adjusting bids near real-time and optimize fuel buying to prevent anticipated short-term spending. That way they can maximize revenue and minimize unnecessary buying costs _(Peters et. al., 2013)._
3.  **Make Smarter Investment Choices:** Models that I use can identify the peak times during the day or week. This information can be used to plan future investments. For example, companies can calculate potential savings from investment in batteries and make an optimization for these situations.

In conclusion, this study demonstrates building data-driven models for electricity demand forecasting. Methodologies and insights are essential for the efficient and reliable operations of modern power systems and all participants in the electricity market. It's crucial to use machine learning models in the electricity demand market _(Gajowniczek, K. and ZÄ…bkowski, T., 2017)_. Energy companies can easily make smart plans, operate more efficiently, and make better decisions in the market by using machine learning models for their business.
